1
00:01:35,554 --> 00:01:39,516
The audience loves detective
movies.

2
00:01:41,018 --> 00:01:44,646
It’s nice to watch a film,
already knowing how it ends.

3
00:01:45,898 --> 00:01:49,902
And in general, it’s flattering
to feel smarter than the authors.

4
00:01:52,487 --> 00:01:56,742
People in the capital claim that
this unbelievable story

5
00:01:57,117 --> 00:01:59,244
happened in Moscow.

6
00:01:59,786 --> 00:02:03,916
Odessans insist it took place
in their city.

7
00:02:05,834 --> 00:02:10,255
Leningrad and Rostov-on-Don
disagree.

8
00:02:12,132 --> 00:02:15,010
Seven cities dispute it
in exactly the same way

9
00:02:15,886 --> 00:02:19,473
as seven cities call themselves
Homer’s birthplace.

10
00:02:19,973 --> 00:02:24,686
It must be said, no one knows
where this story happened—

11
00:02:26,021 --> 00:02:28,941
or whether it happened
at all.

12
00:02:30,192 --> 00:02:34,571
So, as you may have noticed,
it was a dark night.

13
00:02:38,659 --> 00:02:41,828
The unknown man did his best
to remain unnoticed,

14
00:02:43,247 --> 00:02:45,666
and he succeeded.

15
00:02:46,542 --> 00:02:50,587
It was so dark, quiet,
and deserted here

16
00:02:52,172 --> 00:02:55,759
that one couldn’t help
wanting to commit a crime.

17
00:05:21,738 --> 00:05:25,367
- Call Post 2-06\V...
- Yes, sir!

18
00:05:26,201 --> 00:05:28,412
- Block all highways!
- Yes, sir!

19
00:05:28,829 --> 00:05:30,205
Get me the photos urgently—

20
00:05:30,205 --> 00:05:31,915
- ...of the tire tread prints!
- Yes, sir!

21
00:05:32,249 --> 00:05:35,419
Tanya! And you check on the fingerprints.

22
00:05:43,093 --> 00:05:47,931
So, the third car has been stolen
from the same district.

23
00:05:49,391 --> 00:05:53,270
It’s the same hand at work—
skilled and experienced!

24
00:05:55,147 --> 00:05:57,941
That hand works in cotton gloves
from Factory No. 8.

25
00:05:58,233 --> 00:06:02,654
Then it’s not Fedka “Gold Tooth.”
What did the oil analysis show—

26
00:06:02,905 --> 00:06:07,284
the oil the criminal so loves
to pour on garage hinges?

27
00:06:07,701 --> 00:06:09,912
It turned out to be refined oil.

28
00:06:15,125 --> 00:06:19,379
And did you notice that in the yard
where the theft happened,

29
00:06:20,047 --> 00:06:23,550
and on the street nearby, a lot of
cars without garages spend the night?

30
00:06:23,550 --> 00:06:24,718
Yes.

31
00:06:26,345 --> 00:06:30,766
And stealing a car from the street
is easier than from a garage, right?

32
00:06:31,058 --> 00:06:32,768
That is a very accurate observation.

33
00:06:33,060 --> 00:06:36,230
If we apply Stanislavsky’s theory
of the “super-objective,”

34
00:06:36,522 --> 00:06:39,608
a curious thought arises:

35
00:06:39,942 --> 00:06:45,072
the criminal is taking the path
of greatest resistance. But why?

36
00:06:46,573 --> 00:06:50,869
Once we uncover his super-objective,
we’ll catch him.

37
00:06:51,870 --> 00:06:54,081
That’s grand!

38
00:07:00,671 --> 00:07:03,507
Comrade investigator, I forgot
to mention one detail—

39
00:07:04,216 --> 00:07:07,469
- ...maybe it will help.
- I’m listening, comrade victim.

40
00:07:11,348 --> 00:07:17,271
There’s an obscene word scratched
with a nail on my rear fender...

41
00:07:18,564 --> 00:07:22,234
Wait... right... which one?

42
00:08:16,330 --> 00:08:19,500
Hello, Lyuba. I’m back.

43
00:08:21,835 --> 00:08:25,631
Comrades! Fill the trolleybus quicker.
Don’t bunch up at the back.

44
00:08:26,715 --> 00:08:30,761
Yury Ivanovich, the entrance is
on the other side.

45
00:08:30,802 --> 00:08:32,137
Coming.

46
00:09:05,254 --> 00:09:09,007
- Hello, Yakov Mikhailovich!
- Hello, Detochkin!

47
00:09:10,175 --> 00:09:14,096
- So, how’s your uncle from Dushanbe?
- Uncle? Bad.

48
00:09:16,557 --> 00:09:19,768
Last time it was an aunt
from Moldova...

49
00:09:19,810 --> 00:09:21,103
A cousin!

50
00:09:21,979 --> 00:09:24,857
- No, but you said...
- She passed away.

51
00:09:25,107 --> 00:09:29,278
Yeah... we’re all mortal, Detochkin...
we’re all mortal.

52
00:09:30,445 --> 00:09:32,698
And if people didn’t die,

53
00:09:32,698 --> 00:09:36,702
we wouldn’t be able to insure
against death.

54
00:09:38,620 --> 00:09:44,001
You won’t deny, Detochkin,
that I show you consideration.

55
00:09:46,003 --> 00:09:49,590
Every time your relatives fall ill
or die,

56
00:09:50,465 --> 00:09:53,594
I grant you
unpaid leave.

57
00:09:53,594 --> 00:09:56,305
You’re an exceptionally considerate manager.

58
00:09:56,597 --> 00:10:01,685
True, Detochkin, but you have
an awful lot of relatives...

59
00:10:03,145 --> 00:10:05,230
And I have very few staff positions.

60
00:10:05,772 --> 00:10:09,193
You see, your trips
throw off our plan.

61
00:10:09,193 --> 00:10:10,319
I’ll catch up!

62
00:10:12,654 --> 00:10:15,032
Understand, I can’t place

63
00:10:15,032 --> 00:10:18,577
family interests
above public ones.

64
00:10:20,204 --> 00:10:24,124
- I... I’ll catch up!
- Then go catch up.

65
00:10:30,130 --> 00:10:33,258
A policeman stopped me yesterday.
The power of attorney is invalid.

66
00:10:34,551 --> 00:10:38,055
You need to stop by and have it
certified at the notary office.

67
00:10:39,014 --> 00:10:41,600
- Sign here, please.
- Dima, sign it!

68
00:10:48,023 --> 00:10:50,692
To be honest, I don’t even know
why I insure my property.

69
00:10:51,109 --> 00:10:52,319
What about fires?

70
00:10:52,319 --> 00:10:55,989
It would be a shame if such property
burned down for nothing.

71
00:10:56,657 --> 00:10:59,201
Maybe we should insure
our car?

72
00:10:59,201 --> 00:11:00,494
Did you buy a car?

73
00:11:01,995 --> 00:11:06,124
Car insurance is provided
in case of total loss

74
00:11:06,375 --> 00:11:11,255
or damage due to collisions
or natural disasters.

75
00:11:11,630 --> 00:11:15,884
- And in case of theft?
- In case of theft—no.

76
00:11:17,803 --> 00:11:19,513
I’m not so rich

77
00:11:19,513 --> 00:11:22,850
as to pay for natural disasters
as well.

78
00:11:24,852 --> 00:11:27,604
- And where do you keep it?
- Come here!

79
00:11:41,910 --> 00:11:46,582
Beige... not a flashy color...
And you don’t have a garage?

80
00:11:46,582 --> 00:11:48,167
Not yet.

81
00:11:49,626 --> 00:11:52,296
I’m working on it, but it’s
a hard business.

82
00:11:52,963 --> 00:11:56,300
They promise to allocate a spot...
so no garage yet.

83
00:11:56,758 --> 00:12:02,306
But I already got a lock—Japanese.
You can’t pick a key for it.

84
00:12:10,856 --> 00:12:16,320
Yes, hard to pick... even a lockpick
won’t do it.

85
00:12:18,906 --> 00:12:24,620
You’d need an acetylene torch—
and cutting with a torch... that’s such a fuss...

86
00:12:36,924 --> 00:12:39,259
My clever girl.

87
00:13:17,673 --> 00:13:20,676
- Need a lift?
- We’re not going your way.

88
00:13:20,676 --> 00:13:21,552
Suit yourself!

89
00:13:39,611 --> 00:13:44,324
Everyone who doesn’t have a car
dreams of buying one.

90
00:13:45,742 --> 00:13:49,955
And everyone who has a car
dreams of selling it,

91
00:13:51,123 --> 00:13:56,003
and doesn’t only because once you sell it,
you’re left without a car.

92
00:13:57,129 --> 00:14:00,757
Man, more than any other living creature,

93
00:14:01,133 --> 00:14:03,886
loves creating additional difficulties
for himself.

94
00:14:04,386 --> 00:14:08,932
That is exactly what explains
the desire to own a car.

95
00:14:09,725 --> 00:14:13,854
The thought that five and a half thousand
have simply been thrown into the gutter

96
00:14:17,232 --> 00:14:21,320
can poison any happy life.

97
00:14:28,202 --> 00:14:30,412
- Mom!
- You’re here!

98
00:14:34,750 --> 00:14:38,420
I can’t understand what kind of business trips
an insurance agent could have.

99
00:14:38,837 --> 00:14:42,132
Why are you standing there? Lunch is ready,
go wash your hands.

100
00:14:43,258 --> 00:14:45,802
What heavy things are you carrying
in your briefcase?

101
00:14:45,802 --> 00:14:47,971
Necessary work items.

102
00:14:48,347 --> 00:14:51,433
It’s scary to look at you—
you’ve gotten so thin and worn out...

103
00:14:58,106 --> 00:15:03,320
Korchnoi won the chess tournament...
I was rooting for Tal.

104
00:15:03,946 --> 00:15:08,575
He fell behind by half a point...
Don’t laugh at your mother.

105
00:15:21,755 --> 00:15:25,092
Those trips are suspicious
not only to me...

106
00:15:25,092 --> 00:15:26,218
To who else?

107
00:15:29,680 --> 00:15:34,810
Eat the onion soup—recipe
of the great writer Dumas père.

108
00:15:35,102 --> 00:15:38,313
Lyuba finds these trips suspicious. She’s right.

109
00:15:39,523 --> 00:15:43,443
She doesn’t want to marry a bungler.
- Did she tell you that?

110
00:15:52,911 --> 00:15:57,040
No, not now. He’s only just arrived.

111
00:16:05,591 --> 00:16:11,221
That evening Maxim Podberezovikov
was moving in an unknown direction.

112
00:16:12,890 --> 00:16:17,978
From the other end of the city,
in an even more unknown direction,

113
00:16:18,812 --> 00:16:24,735
Yury Detochkin was walking.
They were walking toward fate.

114
00:16:25,611 --> 00:16:28,614
They were drawing closer.

115
00:16:43,879 --> 00:16:47,508
Every investigator invariably has a hobby

116
00:16:48,091 --> 00:16:52,304
to which he devotes the time
free from hunting criminals.

117
00:16:53,222 --> 00:16:55,182
Sherlock Holmes, for example, played the violin;

118
00:16:56,141 --> 00:16:59,019
Maxim Podberezovikov—
amateur theater.

119
00:17:07,236 --> 00:17:11,281
...The development of people’s amateur art

120
00:17:12,282 --> 00:17:17,037
is moving forward in leaps and bounds.
The spirit of the times has finally touched

121
00:17:17,621 --> 00:17:23,627
even us, amateur collectives. We’ve begun
to be consolidated, creating

122
00:17:24,169 --> 00:17:30,425
people’s theaters—one might say, club troupes
are being formed into all-star teams.

123
00:17:32,928 --> 00:17:35,305
Today is a ceremonial day for us.

124
00:17:35,556 --> 00:17:39,768
Today we are creating a new
people’s theater.

125
00:17:40,894 --> 00:17:46,358
I hope it will be a strong organism...
close-knit.

126
00:17:46,859 --> 00:17:49,820
Comrade Detochkin, stop fidgeting,
sit in your place.

127
00:17:58,537 --> 00:18:03,041
Within the welcoming walls of our
House of Culture, all conditions are created

128
00:18:03,667 --> 00:18:08,922
for people of different professions
to be introduced to Melpomene,

129
00:18:09,506 --> 00:18:13,177
who, as is known, was the muse...

130
00:18:14,845 --> 00:18:20,309
Our people’s theater, in particular,
is being created, so to speak, from two

131
00:18:21,226 --> 00:18:27,482
friendly collectives. Uh... from
the police collective and, uh... drivers.

132
00:18:30,444 --> 00:18:34,239
- I recognized you.
- That wasn’t me.

133
00:18:35,407 --> 00:18:39,620
But you... you said: “And who are the judges?”

134
00:18:41,455 --> 00:18:43,916
I never said anything like that about judges.

135
00:18:44,208 --> 00:18:47,294
You did, you did...
Weren’t you the one who played Chatsky?

136
00:18:47,961 --> 00:18:49,755
I... I completely forgot...

137
00:18:50,005 --> 00:18:53,675
And now we’ll be acting together with you
in the same play.

138
00:18:54,510 --> 00:18:57,930
- I’m very glad!
- Me too!

139
00:19:01,391 --> 00:19:07,648
There is an opinion that people’s theaters
will soon... supplant...! At last...

140
00:19:10,317 --> 00:19:13,820
professional theaters!
And that is correct!

141
00:19:19,576 --> 00:19:25,666
An actor who doesn’t receive a salary
will perform with greater inspiration.

142
00:19:26,667 --> 00:19:29,920
After all, besides,
an actor must work somewhere...

143
00:19:32,589 --> 00:19:37,052
It’s wrong if he spends the whole day,
you see, loafing around the theater.

144
00:19:37,302 --> 00:19:40,764
Why, how much better would Yermolova have played
in the evening if during the day she...

145
00:19:41,765 --> 00:19:45,894
you see... worked...
at a grinding machine.

146
00:19:46,186 --> 00:19:50,315
The title of “people’s theater”
places many obligations.

147
00:19:53,026 --> 00:19:57,197
We’ve played all sorts of roles
in our troupes!

148
00:20:01,535 --> 00:20:05,038
Isn’t it time, my friends, we took a swing at William — Shakespeare, that is.

149
00:20:05,455 --> 00:20:11,253
Isn’t it time, my friends, we

150
00:20:11,837 --> 00:20:13,839
And we will!

151
00:21:28,372 --> 00:21:30,874
Transistor radio “Alpinist,” please.
Careful, if you please.

152
00:21:31,208 --> 00:21:34,670
Excuse me, which of you is Dima?
I’m from Oleg Nikolayevich.

153
00:21:35,337 --> 00:21:38,090
- Oleg Nikolayevich who?
- A friend of Leonid Osipovich.

154
00:21:45,514 --> 00:21:49,268
I need a foreign tape recorder—
American or German.

155
00:21:49,977 --> 00:21:52,020
Here’s a very good domestic one.

156
00:21:52,020 --> 00:21:53,689
No, domestic won’t do.

157
00:21:56,567 --> 00:21:58,777
- A foreign one must be “sourced.”
- I understand. How much?

158
00:22:04,491 --> 00:22:07,161
- What’s the matter, citizen?
- Just looking.

159
00:22:09,288 --> 00:22:13,167
What is this, a zoo or something?
Go watch the TV over there.

160
00:22:15,252 --> 00:22:19,089
- Fifty.
- Fifty?

161
00:22:19,756 --> 00:22:23,760
- Pull yourself together.
- Need to find one, bring it in. Italy?

162
00:22:24,511 --> 00:22:25,971
We’ll have to hold off...

163
00:22:25,971 --> 00:22:28,390
- ...leave your phone number...
- All right.

164
00:22:40,152 --> 00:22:42,821
- “Belomor,” please.
- No “Belomor.”

165
00:22:46,408 --> 00:22:49,661
Well... what do you have? Then give me
“Friend” cigarettes.

166
00:23:49,179 --> 00:23:51,348
Taxi! Taxi! Taxi!

167
00:23:57,938 --> 00:24:01,859
Please! I beg you!
I’m late. Is this your car?

168
00:24:02,359 --> 00:24:03,777
- No.
- But are you the driver?

169
00:24:03,777 --> 00:24:04,236
No, no.

170
00:24:04,611 --> 00:24:08,490
- Then what are you doing here?
- I want to steal a car, and you’re in the way.

171
00:24:08,866 --> 00:24:12,119
Then please steal it with me,
I’m late for my train.

172
00:24:15,956 --> 00:24:22,045
Ah! Get in. But you are becoming an accomplice.

173
00:24:24,965 --> 00:24:28,719
There! I warned you!

174
00:24:39,980 --> 00:24:42,691
Get him! There he is! Caught him!
Get him, get the thief!

175
00:24:46,320 --> 00:24:50,157
Get him! Don’t let him go!
What a thief!

176
00:24:55,204 --> 00:24:57,998
I’m not a thief! I’m late for my train.
Please, here’s my ticket!

177
00:24:58,415 --> 00:25:01,376
Came prepared! Look how prudent he is! Huh?

178
00:25:12,137 --> 00:25:15,807
Finally! Hurry! They caught the crook!
He tried to steal my car!

179
00:25:17,935 --> 00:25:21,688
- Who’s the owner?
- Me... I mean, we are.

180
00:25:22,689 --> 00:25:25,651
I’m not a thief. I’m late for my train,
and he took my ticket.

181
00:25:25,984 --> 00:25:28,070
- Your documents?
- Here. My ticket.

182
00:25:28,070 --> 00:25:28,737
- And yours.
- What?

183
00:25:31,532 --> 00:25:35,953
- We won’t sort this out here.
Who’s the witness? - Me! …What’s going on?

184
00:25:37,162 --> 00:25:40,666
I’m not a thief. The thief got away.
Unfortunately I didn’t remember his face...

185
00:25:40,916 --> 00:25:44,586
I’m late for my train!
Though I’m already too late.

186
00:25:57,099 --> 00:25:59,643
- Is it yours?
- Why, no! Heaven forbid!

187
00:26:02,729 --> 00:26:07,568
Yes, I’m a witness. A witness. Me.
I look better in profile...

188
00:26:09,403 --> 00:26:11,321
So, I’ll start from the very beginning.

189
00:26:12,281 --> 00:26:16,451
They didn’t bring me “Belomor” today.
Well... they didn’t, so they didn’t.

190
00:26:20,455 --> 00:26:22,833
Could you make it shorter?

191
00:26:23,250 --> 00:26:27,296
Young man... in your profession,
there’s no need to rush.

192
00:26:27,546 --> 00:26:31,717
“Belomor” is a detail for the investigation!
And that very man,

193
00:26:32,301 --> 00:26:36,013
the one who climbed into your car,
also first asked for “Belomor,”

194
00:26:36,513 --> 00:26:38,390
and then bought “Friend” cigarettes,

195
00:26:38,390 --> 00:26:40,809
30 kopeks a pack,
with a little dog on the label.

196
00:26:41,435 --> 00:26:47,149
And then I thought:
“Why is he nervous? Why?”

197
00:26:48,358 --> 00:26:51,111
Stop! Stop, stop! What do you keep thinking about?

198
00:26:52,196 --> 00:26:54,448
Every player must know the part by heart

199
00:26:54,448 --> 00:26:56,492
and you don’t need to run dumbly
around the stage.

200
00:26:57,159 --> 00:26:59,578
You have to act with your head!

201
00:27:00,162 --> 00:27:04,458
And don’t be rude, or I’ll send you off the field...
uh... off the rehearsal!

202
00:27:05,375 --> 00:27:08,545
- I’m not being rude, I...
- B-r-e-a-k!

203
00:27:09,796 --> 00:27:14,259
Yevgeny Alexandrovich, this line:
“Leave it, for God’s sake!”

204
00:27:14,551 --> 00:27:17,095
Ah... leave it! Break!

205
00:27:19,431 --> 00:27:23,268
- What am I, some kid to him or what?
- Don’t get upset! Come on...

206
00:27:26,563 --> 00:27:29,733
- What are you smoking?
- “Friend” cigarettes.

207
00:27:31,151 --> 00:27:34,905
Yes-yes... “Friend” cigarettes...
dog on the label... thirty kopeks...

208
00:27:36,406 --> 00:27:39,284
Normally I smoke “Belomor,” but there wasn’t any.

209
00:27:39,535 --> 00:27:43,455
There wasn’t any “Belomor,” exactly—
that’s why he bought “Friend” cigarettes.

210
00:27:43,789 --> 00:27:46,250
- Who’s “he”?
- The criminal.

211
00:27:47,584 --> 00:27:48,919
What criminal?

212
00:27:48,919 --> 00:27:53,090
A modern one—I’d even say,
a new type of criminal.

213
00:27:53,507 --> 00:27:57,386
What did crooks used to leave
at the crime scene? - What?

214
00:27:57,845 --> 00:28:00,764
Caps, cigarette butts—and now...
Shakespeare!

215
00:28:00,764 --> 00:28:03,642
Don’t be afraid—
there are no bloodstains here!

216
00:28:04,768 --> 00:28:09,982
- So you’re an investigator?
- Yes. I handle car theft cases.

217
00:28:10,732 --> 00:28:16,113
No fingerprints. The criminal works in gloves.

218
00:28:17,906 --> 00:28:22,244
- But you’re not interested?
- No... very interested!

219
00:28:23,203 --> 00:28:28,333
You see, there’s no library stamp, no...

220
00:28:33,422 --> 00:28:38,260
I’m saying: no library stamp,
and no owner’s name.

221
00:28:38,510 --> 00:28:41,180
You know how some people sign their books?

222
00:28:41,180 --> 00:28:42,890
I do, but I don’t sign mine.

223
00:28:44,266 --> 00:28:47,686
There’s a gang operating in the city.
Stealing private cars.

224
00:28:47,936 --> 00:28:50,814
Over the year, four cars have been stolen
from one district.

225
00:28:50,814 --> 00:28:51,773
Three!

226
00:28:52,733 --> 00:28:54,985
There, you’ve heard too.
Yes, three.

227
00:28:55,235 --> 00:29:00,199
They failed to steal the fourth.
But we’ll put an end to this soon.

228
00:29:00,532 --> 00:29:05,829
- How?
- We detained one member of the gang.

229
00:29:07,331 --> 00:29:10,709
A respectable man—an engineer.
Wife’s a doctor. Two kids.

230
00:29:15,714 --> 00:29:18,258
- What does he look like?
- Sort of small.

231
00:29:18,258 --> 00:29:19,468
- Roundish?
- Yes...

232
00:29:21,386 --> 00:29:24,640
- And... and you arrested him?
- Why take such a harsh measure?

233
00:29:25,516 --> 00:29:29,019
He was about to run off to a resort,
but I made him sign a travel restriction.

234
00:29:29,436 --> 00:29:34,525
What if he’s not an accomplice? A respectable man—
and you deprived him of his vacation?

235
00:29:35,317 --> 00:29:38,111
My instinct tells me he’s not guilty.

236
00:29:39,029 --> 00:29:41,573
But the final clarification is a matter
of a few days.

237
00:29:42,157 --> 00:29:47,371
I already know the ringleader’s
distinguishing features...

238
00:29:48,163 --> 00:29:52,793
Tall... wears a raincoat,
a hat, carries a briefcase...

239
00:29:54,586 --> 00:29:58,257
and the main feature—hunched...

240
00:30:10,853 --> 00:30:12,938
And how are you going to catch the ringleader?

241
00:30:13,981 --> 00:30:16,692
Comrades! Everyone for the second half, please!

242
00:30:19,361 --> 00:30:22,990
We’d like a trap for large game.

243
00:30:23,949 --> 00:30:27,828
- Hunting fox, or wolf?
- Bear. - He’s joking.

244
00:30:35,002 --> 00:30:38,046
Tell me... how does it work?

245
00:30:38,881 --> 00:30:40,340
You put the bait here.

246
00:30:40,340 --> 00:30:42,634
- You have bait?
- I do, I do.

247
00:30:44,928 --> 00:30:49,558
The predator smells the bait... sneaks up,
sneaks up... and the beast is caught!

248
00:30:51,268 --> 00:30:54,021
- Lovely!
- Write it up!

249
00:31:06,700 --> 00:31:09,620
- I think it’s all good.
- Lovely! Bring ice cream...

250
00:31:34,311 --> 00:31:38,857
Sima! You’re not in the woods! Guys,
don’t split up! Stick together!

251
00:33:23,795 --> 00:33:24,963
Semitsvetov! Dima!

252
00:33:24,963 --> 00:33:27,382
- She’s blonde!
- Beige-ish!

253
00:33:33,388 --> 00:33:37,601
Guys, when I’ve been drinking, I don’t get behind the wheel.

254
00:33:42,648 --> 00:33:48,278
Take us for a ride, Dima! Take us for a ride,
Dima... Take us for a ride, Di-ma!

255
00:33:50,864 --> 00:33:52,491
Quiet! Quiet! Quiet!

256
00:33:53,492 --> 00:33:56,161
They’ve invented this little tube at the police—
you... phew!

257
00:33:56,411 --> 00:33:59,039
You breathe into it and it immediately shows
whether a person drank or not.

258
00:33:59,039 --> 00:34:00,374
And if you did—they take your license.

259
00:34:01,625 --> 00:34:04,878
- I’m going anyway!
- Sima, this isn’t the beach!

260
00:34:05,629 --> 00:34:09,258
- Why are you lying down? It’s polished!
- So what!

261
00:34:35,617 --> 00:34:37,661
- Listen, I’m r-really smashed!
- Yeah!

262
00:34:37,953 --> 00:34:41,915
I must place myself
in a horizontal position.

263
00:35:21,955 --> 00:35:25,125
- Who is it?
- Lyuba, it’s me!

264
00:35:27,044 --> 00:35:30,797
What is it?

265
00:35:33,967 --> 00:35:35,802
What happened?

266
00:35:36,929 --> 00:35:41,975
Lyuba, you see, they’ve set traps everywhere!
- My God!

267
00:35:44,478 --> 00:35:47,898
I’m miserable, miserable—
I’m so unlucky!

268
00:35:48,732 --> 00:35:52,986
The criminal attempted twice
on the same car.

269
00:35:54,488 --> 00:35:59,576
Not a coincidence. I think he meant
to steal your car specifically.

270
00:35:59,827 --> 00:36:02,830
Reasonable... I figured that out too.

271
00:36:04,957 --> 00:36:08,544
But you shouldn’t set a trap for a living person.

272
00:36:08,794 --> 00:36:12,256
You couldn’t protect us from the bandit,
so we had to take up self-defense.

273
00:36:12,548 --> 00:36:16,093
Why did he latch on to your car in particular?

274
00:36:20,973 --> 00:36:24,643
You don’t suspect anyone
among your acquaintances?

275
00:36:27,145 --> 00:36:29,773
Our acquaintances are perfectly decent people.

276
00:36:30,983 --> 00:36:34,778
Well, perhaps someone envies you?

277
00:36:35,028 --> 00:36:38,782
Envies what? You’re asking strange questions.

278
00:36:44,872 --> 00:36:48,834
Check the clinics—see whether anyone came in

279
00:36:48,834 --> 00:36:51,128
with a characteristic leg injury.

280
00:36:52,838 --> 00:36:56,925
Let’s set up surveillance
on your car!

281
00:36:58,677 --> 00:37:02,181
No, thank you...
We’re putting up a garage tomorrow.

282
00:37:12,357 --> 00:37:17,863
How can you not come? Look, the director will give you a penalty kick!

283
00:37:21,867 --> 00:37:27,831
Ah, your leg hurts! Well then, lie down...
Of course, I’ll pass it on... get well!

284
00:37:33,212 --> 00:37:38,967
- Who’s the one with the leg?
- The right person.

285
00:37:40,636 --> 00:37:43,722
- All right then, call.
- When?

286
00:37:44,515 --> 00:37:47,518
When your car gets stolen.

287
00:38:04,076 --> 00:38:06,453
Dima, they’re taking away Toptunov’s dacha!

288
00:38:06,453 --> 00:38:08,705
- Who’s taking it?
- Are you an idiot?

289
00:38:12,626 --> 00:38:14,670
Daddy, they’re taking away Toptunov’s dacha.

290
00:38:14,920 --> 00:38:21,176
And they’re right to take it—long overdue!
We must fight crooks, for instance.

291
00:38:21,927 --> 00:38:25,055
Why is he a crook? The man knows how to live.

292
00:38:25,472 --> 00:38:29,977
Tell me this: on what salary did the deputy director
of a knitwear factory

293
00:38:30,269 --> 00:38:34,106
build himself a two-story mansion?

294
00:38:34,356 --> 00:38:36,900
- That’s his business!
- No, it’s ours!

295
00:38:37,526 --> 00:38:43,198
We will mercilessly fight those
living on unearned income!

296
00:38:43,448 --> 00:38:46,577
- Hush, Daddy!
- Ah, scared, are you?

297
00:38:47,744 --> 00:38:51,415
I’ll give you a knee, I swear,
and you’ll fly off my land!

298
00:38:51,665 --> 00:38:55,961
Dad, I’m sick of your drill-sergeant humor!
What do you mean, “a knee”? Why?

299
00:38:56,336 --> 00:38:59,631
Why are you getting uppity, son-in-law?
Who do you think you are?

300
00:38:59,923 --> 00:39:02,259
This is my dacha!

301
00:39:03,760 --> 00:39:07,264
Let everyone hear it—this is my dacha!

302
00:39:08,056 --> 00:39:12,352
It’s registered in your name!
But it’s being built with my money.

303
00:39:13,312 --> 00:39:15,355
Prove it!
Oh, stop it already!

304
00:39:15,689 --> 00:39:20,569
You live in this world on a power of attorney!

305
00:39:20,986 --> 00:39:25,782
The car’s in your wife’s name, the dacha’s in mine—
you own nothing. You’re a nobody!

306
00:39:27,242 --> 00:39:32,372
Why! Why do I have to live like this?
Lord, why? Why?

307
00:39:34,917 --> 00:39:38,170
I, a man with a university degree,
have to hide, adapt,

308
00:39:38,795 --> 00:39:44,176
wiggle, maneuver! Why can’t I live
freely, openly?

309
00:39:45,385 --> 00:39:49,806
Oh, when will it all end! Never!
What do you even mean by that?

310
00:39:51,934 --> 00:39:54,061
Do you know what I can,
plain and simple,

311
00:39:54,061 --> 00:39:55,229
do to you for this?

312
00:39:56,980 --> 00:40:00,818
- I know... I know...
- He’s scared!

313
00:40:00,818 --> 00:40:03,237
Have pity on him, Daddy!

314
00:40:04,196 --> 00:40:09,743
This type must always remember
who I am! And he’s a common crook!

315
00:40:11,995 --> 00:40:16,250
Still, I ought to give you a knee!

316
00:42:54,992 --> 00:42:57,452
- Who is it?
- Lyuba, it’s me!

317
00:42:58,662 --> 00:43:04,168
- What happened? Another trap?
- No, this time it all worked out.

318
00:43:10,007 --> 00:43:14,136
You’re leaving? On a trip?

319
00:43:15,220 --> 00:43:18,557
Now? At night?

320
00:43:18,849 --> 00:43:22,186
It’s not my fault... I have to...
because, you see,

321
00:43:23,228 --> 00:43:26,899
a “business trip” is quite
a complicated undertaking.

322
00:43:33,322 --> 00:43:37,075
Lyuba! Why get
so upset.

323
00:43:37,493 --> 00:43:42,706
I’ll be back in a few days.
I’ll write to you from there. Do you hear?

324
00:43:50,130 --> 00:43:55,010
Lyuba! I’m very upset too.
See?

325
00:44:17,991 --> 00:44:21,578
Hello. You know, our right turn signal sticks.

326
00:44:22,246 --> 00:44:25,999
And when shifting gears,
there’s this sound...

327
00:44:25,999 --> 00:44:27,251
We’ll listen.

328
00:44:30,462 --> 00:44:33,757
And the day before yesterday the whole day
the car smelled of gasoline.

329
00:44:33,757 --> 00:44:34,842
We’ll sniff.

330
00:45:02,411 --> 00:45:04,621
Where’s the car?

331
00:45:48,874 --> 00:45:51,001
- Comrade chief...
- Hello!

332
00:45:52,794 --> 00:45:57,257
I see you’re driving alone. Help me,
please, start this heap of junk.

333
00:45:58,509 --> 00:46:02,679
- Start a motorcycle?
- Yes. Can’t manage it alone.

334
00:46:15,025 --> 00:46:17,945
No, it’s just the battery’s dead.

335
00:46:18,612 --> 00:46:22,574
I’ve asked the bosses a thousand times
to move me to a new motorcycle.

336
00:46:23,408 --> 00:46:26,328
Yeah... with an old battery
it’s no life.

337
00:46:27,287 --> 00:46:30,499
- So? Three-four, ready?
- Let’s try.

338
00:46:36,296 --> 00:46:40,217
Come on, get a running start!
A running start, a running start.

339
00:46:52,604 --> 00:46:57,234
- All right... stop! I see you’re worn out.
- A bit.

340
00:46:58,652 --> 00:47:02,072
- Now let me give you a ride.
- What’s the point?

341
00:47:02,364 --> 00:47:06,660
Listen, pal. Let’s hook it to your Volga.
Do you have a tow rope?

342
00:47:06,952 --> 00:47:10,455
Who knows what’s in there...

343
00:47:15,127 --> 00:47:19,173
I don’t remember. I’ll look now.

344
00:47:33,854 --> 00:47:35,564
Got a tow rope!

345
00:47:38,942 --> 00:47:41,153
Great!

346
00:47:47,951 --> 00:47:49,703
All right! Thanks, pal, you saved me.

347
00:47:49,703 --> 00:47:51,622
- Man to man is a friend.
- Exactly.

348
00:47:56,668 --> 00:47:59,546
Trouble happened to me—you helped me.

349
00:47:59,546 --> 00:48:01,507
If it happens to you—I’ll help.

350
00:48:01,798 --> 00:48:07,346
And together we do one common cause:
you in your way, and I in mine.

351
00:48:10,224 --> 00:48:13,101
Tell me, pal, is there a telegraph around here?

352
00:48:13,101 --> 00:48:14,728
Not far. Hop on, I’ll show you.

353
00:48:43,632 --> 00:48:48,720
Please grant five days unpaid leave
due to the sudden grave

354
00:48:49,221 --> 00:48:54,434
condition... grave condition...
of my beloved nephew.

355
00:49:07,197 --> 00:49:12,286
All right, all right... I understand!
I’m writing... done.

356
00:49:21,962 --> 00:49:24,423
- Taking a rest?
- Uh-huh...

357
00:49:47,654 --> 00:49:52,659
- Something happen?
- No, nothing, nothing.

358
00:49:58,040 --> 00:49:59,500
- Who’s the owner?
- Me.

359
00:49:59,500 --> 00:50:00,876
Car documents.

360
00:50:10,135 --> 00:50:11,887
Sorry.

361
00:51:16,118 --> 00:51:19,997
A chase! What detective plot
can do without one?

362
00:51:20,539 --> 00:51:25,961
One runs, the other gives chase—
such is the immutable law of the genre.

363
00:51:26,545 --> 00:51:32,134
A detective without a chase is like
life without love.

364
00:52:08,170 --> 00:52:12,341
Detochkin loved children. He couldn’t do otherwise.

365
00:52:13,425 --> 00:52:15,594
Detochkin understood it was the end.

366
00:52:15,844 --> 00:52:21,683
He wanted to close his eyes,
but he was afraid of running over a Young Pioneer.

367
00:52:23,101 --> 00:52:28,398
But the inspector also loved children
and was no less noble than Detochkin.

368
00:55:29,913 --> 00:55:32,249
- Got you, brother!
- Yeah, got me!

369
00:55:32,666 --> 00:55:37,713
You won’t get away from the police... damn it!
Hold on a second!

370
00:55:39,173 --> 00:55:43,802
- You... you wait, don’t drive off!
- What is it, brother?

371
00:55:44,469 --> 00:55:47,890
What, what... well, again, you see,
the battery...

372
00:55:48,348 --> 00:55:52,519
I warned you. With an old battery—it’s no life.

373
00:55:53,187 --> 00:55:58,233
I always feared it. Important work comes up,
and it lets me down.

374
00:55:59,651 --> 00:56:01,904
There! They didn’t move me
to a new motorcycle.

375
00:56:01,904 --> 00:56:02,696
My sympathies.

376
00:56:03,530 --> 00:56:06,617
- Bad luck for you.
- But good luck for you!

377
00:56:06,867 --> 00:56:10,245
Between the two of us, someone had to get lucky.

378
00:56:11,497 --> 00:56:14,500
So what do we do, brother?

379
00:56:17,628 --> 00:56:20,172
And why were you running from me?

380
00:56:21,548 --> 00:56:25,135
Habit. You chase, I run.

381
00:56:25,511 --> 00:56:30,807
And I’ve got a habit too. You run,
I chase... you could’ve gotten out, helped.

382
00:56:32,434 --> 00:56:35,896
We could’ve hooked it to your Volga,
like last time.

383
00:56:45,030 --> 00:56:50,744
No way! I’ve already seen how you repay kindness.
Sorry!

384
00:57:15,269 --> 00:57:17,521
Stop interfering!
Look, the police!

385
00:57:17,771 --> 00:57:21,650
Lock the garage! Proceed!

386
00:57:22,943 --> 00:57:24,945
Lift!

387
00:57:39,084 --> 00:57:41,128
Lower!

388
00:57:42,921 --> 00:57:46,341
I always said he was
a talented criminal.

389
00:57:46,592 --> 00:57:50,721
Maybe even... more talented
than me.

390
00:57:58,145 --> 00:58:00,606
Good grief, all the money is in one-ruble notes!

391
00:58:00,898 --> 00:58:04,860
Don’t distract me, or I’ll have to start over.

392
00:58:08,280 --> 00:58:11,158
Five thousand five hundred! That’s it!

393
00:58:12,367 --> 00:58:15,954
Why is all your money in one-ruble notes?
That’s suspicious. Not good!

394
00:58:17,039 --> 00:58:19,541
And what are you, a prosecutor?

395
00:58:20,167 --> 00:58:23,962
I’m not asking where the car came from,
why there are no documents.

396
00:58:24,588 --> 00:58:28,342
And I can be frank.
I stole this car.

397
00:58:32,513 --> 00:58:35,474
I can be frank too. I’m a pastor.

398
00:58:36,141 --> 00:58:42,397
These rubles are donations to him! Come on!
Just a little left!

399
00:58:44,983 --> 00:58:47,694
And you believe in God?

400
00:58:49,404 --> 00:58:54,576
Everyone believes—some believe
God exists, others believe He doesn’t.

401
00:58:55,452 --> 00:59:00,707
Neither can be proven!
Going to recount?

402
00:59:01,875 --> 00:59:03,836
I am!

403
00:59:30,529 --> 00:59:34,116
There! As promised...
a Grundig tape recorder.

404
00:59:34,116 --> 00:59:34,992
But is it new?

405
00:59:35,409 --> 00:59:39,288
- Absolutely new. Personally checked it.
- Then write it up. I remember everything.

406
00:59:41,790 --> 00:59:45,377
- Eighty!
- What? You said fifty!

407
00:59:46,712 --> 00:59:50,757
- Personal circumstances have changed.
- You know, that’s plain robbery!

408
00:59:51,258 --> 00:59:54,511
I’m not insisting. It’ll be gone in a second.
A classy item...

409
00:59:55,053 --> 00:59:58,390
- ...four tracks... stereo.
- Write it up!

410
01:00:06,106 --> 01:00:09,067
Citizen, it’s sold. Don’t touch it with your hands.
It’s sold.

411
01:00:10,569 --> 01:00:14,823
Why did he still want to steal your car specifically?

412
01:00:25,709 --> 01:00:30,839
- What’s wrong with you?
- They caught me...

413
01:00:31,840 --> 01:00:34,259
I’m done for... an investigator came to see me.

414
01:00:34,259 --> 01:00:35,886
You steal — you get locked up.

415
01:00:37,471 --> 01:00:39,806
Semyon Vasilyevich, this is my house.
— Your house is jail.

416
01:00:39,806 --> 01:00:40,849
Your house is jail.

417
01:00:42,684 --> 01:00:44,645
Inka, Inka! What do we do? What do we do?
Inka, what do we do?

418
01:00:44,937 --> 01:00:47,397
Pack a toothbrush.

419
01:00:50,901 --> 01:00:54,947
Dima, don’t worry! You’ve got to grease
the investigator’s palm!

420
01:00:55,656 --> 01:00:57,699
Are you out of your mind? Grease his palm!
You’re crazy!

421
01:00:57,991 --> 01:01:00,661
- Give him a lot! Then he’ll take it!
- Silence! Attention!

422
01:01:01,036 --> 01:01:02,913
I won’t allow it! Shame!

423
01:01:03,163 --> 01:01:05,123
Dad, take your lectures back to your market stall.

424
01:01:05,374 --> 01:01:09,253
I sell strawberries grown
with my own hands.

425
01:01:09,503 --> 01:01:13,090
And for bribes, not only a son-in-law—
I’ll grind my own daughter into dust!

426
01:01:13,340 --> 01:01:15,926
It’s fine! Prison will re-educate you.

427
01:01:15,926 --> 01:01:18,804
In ten years you’ll come back
a different man!

428
01:01:19,054 --> 01:01:21,598
Put the little bird down!

429
01:01:30,149 --> 01:01:34,736
One should marry an orphan...

430
01:01:50,669 --> 01:01:55,507
Don’t doubt it, I have that money—
here... a full briefcase.

431
01:01:57,801 --> 01:02:00,053
Do you really want to transfer

432
01:02:00,053 --> 01:02:02,347
- ...this amount to an orphanage?
- Yes.

433
01:02:02,598 --> 01:02:07,102
Were you raised in that home?
Are these your personal savings?

434
01:02:08,645 --> 01:02:13,484
Well, how to put it... generally...
I had a hand in it too.

435
01:02:14,902 --> 01:02:17,738
Hello! I need Yury Ivanovich Detochkin.

436
01:02:19,656 --> 01:02:22,242
- I’m Yura’s mother.
- Very nice to meet you.

437
01:02:24,536 --> 01:02:26,830
I’m from the people’s theater.

438
01:02:27,706 --> 01:02:29,917
I’m very glad Yura acts in the theater.

439
01:02:30,501 --> 01:02:33,587
- I think he has ability.
- He has real talent.

440
01:02:34,004 --> 01:02:37,799
- He missed rehearsal...
- Dearie, he’s on a business trip.

441
01:02:40,052 --> 01:02:45,182
I hate his “business trips.”
He bolts in the middle of the night, disappears.

442
01:02:45,724 --> 01:02:49,770
Lyuba’s right—something’s not right.
Lyuba is Yura’s fiancée.

443
01:02:52,606 --> 01:02:55,692
He’s so... old-fashioned.
He’s been courting her for ages.

444
01:02:58,403 --> 01:03:01,657
They met when he came
to insure her...

445
01:03:02,866 --> 01:03:07,287
Tell me, what kind of business trips
can an insurance agent have?

446
01:03:09,206 --> 01:03:12,334
- What’s your profession?
- Investigator.

447
01:03:12,334 --> 01:03:13,877
Then you figure it out!

448
01:03:15,087 --> 01:03:18,382
When I was young,
an investigator courted me.

449
01:03:18,882 --> 01:03:22,344
But I married a Red Army soldier.

450
01:03:24,179 --> 01:03:29,351
We sang: “Our locomotive races ahead,
the commune is our stop!”

451
01:03:33,981 --> 01:03:38,110
- And when did he leave, and for how long?
- Three days ago, at night.

452
01:03:38,819 --> 01:03:41,989
And the strangest thing: he came to say goodbye
to Lyuba in some Volga.

453
01:03:44,158 --> 01:03:47,327
- Ah! He took a taxi!
- No, he was driving himself.

454
01:03:51,206 --> 01:03:55,502
- Does Yury Ivanovich drive?
- Yura? He worked as a driver for 10 years.

455
01:03:56,962 --> 01:04:00,299
Then he had an accident, got a concussion.

456
01:04:02,426 --> 01:04:04,720
The doctors advised him not to drive for a while,

457
01:04:04,720 --> 01:04:06,638
so he became an insurance agent.

458
01:04:15,564 --> 01:04:17,608
What’s wrong?

459
01:04:19,776 --> 01:04:21,904
To what city did you send
your employee Detochkin

460
01:04:21,904 --> 01:04:23,363
on a business trip?

461
01:04:23,655 --> 01:04:26,283
I didn’t send him anywhere.

462
01:04:28,368 --> 01:04:32,414
Detochkin has a great many
chronically ill relatives

463
01:04:33,290 --> 01:04:36,543
in different cities of the Soviet Union.

464
01:04:37,628 --> 01:04:43,884
I recently received
a telegram... here it is. Here.

465
01:04:46,887 --> 01:04:53,143
His next beloved nephew fell ill.
He took unpaid leave.

466
01:05:10,160 --> 01:05:15,040
Maxim was beside himself. Memories
burned his heart.

467
01:05:16,291 --> 01:05:21,922
How cleverly Detochkin hid his interest
in the hunt for the ringleader! Hypocrite!

468
01:05:23,632 --> 01:05:27,094
How he stole a car
with the help of a crane!

469
01:05:27,094 --> 01:05:28,887
A vile schemer, a thief!

470
01:05:30,973 --> 01:05:37,229
He betrayed what was dearest—friendship!
And there is no mercy for such a man.

471
01:06:10,053 --> 01:06:15,559
Mom? It’s me. I just arrived...
I’m fine... is everything calm at home?

472
01:06:17,144 --> 01:06:18,353
Did anyone come by?

473
01:06:18,353 --> 01:06:20,814
You’ve played yourself with that people’s theater.

474
01:06:21,231 --> 01:06:23,192
An investigator stopped by to see you.

475
01:06:23,484 --> 01:06:27,863
- Defend yourself, sir!
- At your service...

476
01:06:36,872 --> 01:06:40,626
I have the honor to attack you...

477
01:06:42,294 --> 01:06:45,923
- Where have you been?
- Damn it, I was on a business trip!

478
01:06:46,840 --> 01:06:48,133
And how is the nephew?

479
01:06:48,133 --> 01:06:49,635
- What nephew?
- The beloved one!

480
01:06:52,304 --> 01:06:57,851
And the wolf trap? And the bad leg?
And “Friend” cigarettes?

481
01:07:01,522 --> 01:07:05,692
Stop ad-libbing! In Shakespeare’s time
there were no “Friend” cigarettes!

482
01:07:06,360 --> 01:07:09,488
And besides, why have you switched
to prose?

483
01:07:13,450 --> 01:07:15,702
- Podberezovikov!
- Yes?

484
01:07:15,702 --> 01:07:17,996
What do you keep thinking about?

485
01:07:19,164 --> 01:07:22,251
Stop it! Stop waving your saber!

486
01:07:35,806 --> 01:07:38,642
What a blow!
Easy!

487
01:07:40,227 --> 01:07:42,354
- Where is he?
- He’s coming to!

488
01:07:42,354 --> 01:07:43,981
- Alive!
- Break!

489
01:08:02,040 --> 01:08:05,460
- How many cars did you sell?
- Four.

490
01:08:05,794 --> 01:08:09,631
Let’s say four. A decent sum—
a whole fortune.

491
01:08:10,757 --> 01:08:15,304
Where did you come from like this:
a mother so nice, singing about locomotives?

492
01:08:22,144 --> 01:08:26,565
- Excuse me, are you crazy?
- No, I even have a certificate.

493
01:08:28,567 --> 01:08:30,819
Some actor!

494
01:08:31,445 --> 01:08:35,324
I always said: a real crook,
as a rule, is a good actor!

495
01:08:36,617 --> 01:08:40,954
You stole only from those you considered crooks.
I figured it out right away!

496
01:08:41,997 --> 01:08:46,126
Think the court will shave off a year or two?

497
01:08:52,007 --> 01:08:54,760
Where do you hide your capital?

498
01:08:54,760 --> 01:08:56,887
- Here.
- Aha! I see!

499
01:09:00,766 --> 01:09:02,976
Hello! Why didn’t you tell me at once?

500
01:09:03,644 --> 01:09:08,023
Please go with your friend
to a separate office.

501
01:09:08,357 --> 01:09:12,486
Raya! Lyuda!

502
01:09:13,153 --> 01:09:17,741
They’ll bring fresh beer in a moment—
just delivered—and serve dried roach...

503
01:09:17,991 --> 01:09:21,328
- And the fish was just caught!
- Your friend’s a joker!

504
01:09:22,996 --> 01:09:27,835
Tell me, is there any news
about the car?

505
01:09:27,835 --> 01:09:29,253
There will be soon.

506
01:09:34,716 --> 01:09:38,887
- Let’s go from here.
- Let’s stay a little longer, if we may.

507
01:09:39,179 --> 01:09:43,433
I doubt they’ll feed me in prison
the way they do here.

508
01:09:44,643 --> 01:09:48,730
- What’s that?
- A change of underwear, just in case.

509
01:09:52,609 --> 01:09:57,322
- And this?
- Certificates, receipts, documents...

510
01:09:57,573 --> 01:10:02,703
- What documents? Where’s the money?
- That is the money.

511
01:10:08,333 --> 01:10:13,046
What? You transferred the money
to children’s homes?

512
01:10:13,046 --> 01:10:14,590
Uh-huh.

513
01:10:18,302 --> 01:10:22,181
- And how much did you keep for yourself?
- I kept nothing.

514
01:10:22,931 --> 01:10:25,517
Only for travel and per diem.

515
01:10:41,950 --> 01:10:46,580
Yes, dear viewer, Detochkin
didn’t take the money for himself.

516
01:10:48,290 --> 01:10:53,712
He may be a thief, but he’s
a selfless, honest man.

517
01:10:58,759 --> 01:11:00,719
They spread accounting documents on the table.

518
01:11:01,803 --> 01:11:05,307
That’s an audit... bring them our “house beer.”

519
01:11:05,307 --> 01:11:06,475
Right.

520
01:11:13,357 --> 01:11:17,194
I didn’t sell the first car.
I left it with the police in Kursk.

521
01:11:17,611 --> 01:11:20,531
I stuck a detailed explanation note
to the windshield

522
01:11:20,781 --> 01:11:24,701
and went to the station and returned
to Moscow.

523
01:11:36,421 --> 01:11:40,050
And... with the second car,
an injustice happened.

524
01:11:41,343 --> 01:11:43,470
I drove it to the police too,

525
01:11:43,470 --> 01:11:46,932
and left a note too,
that the owner was a crook!

526
01:11:48,600 --> 01:11:54,523
But they returned it to the owner...
that’s when I decided to sell them!

527
01:12:10,539 --> 01:12:13,458
I love you!

528
01:12:19,965 --> 01:12:26,221
Here! The warrant for your arrest!
And now give it to me!

529
01:12:27,097 --> 01:12:29,016
Take it!

530
01:12:30,434 --> 01:12:36,398
- And now I’ll tear it up!
- Maxim! Maxim. Don’t you dare!

531
01:12:37,316 --> 01:12:40,027
- Yura!
- Don’t you dare! You’ll get in trouble!

532
01:12:42,029 --> 01:12:44,281
Maxim! Guys! We’re friends! Guys!

533
01:12:44,490 --> 01:12:48,202
Dad! Everything’s fine! Dad!
Everything’s fine! Dad!

534
01:12:51,371 --> 01:12:56,710
Then take it for yourself!
I’m giving it to you as a gift!

535
01:13:04,426 --> 01:13:07,679
Come in! Goodbye!
Goodbye!

536
01:13:14,311 --> 01:13:17,356
Friend! Friend!

537
01:13:18,273 --> 01:13:24,530
If I fall ill, I won’t go
to the doctors.

538
01:13:27,616 --> 01:13:33,539
I’ll turn to my friends—
don’t think I’m delirious...

539
01:13:43,006 --> 01:13:48,554
Listen, friend! Don’t lock me up
before the premiere, I beg you!

540
01:13:48,846 --> 01:13:53,642
I won’t lock you up at all.
Live free!

541
01:13:53,934 --> 01:13:56,854
What a part! It happens once in a lifetime, you know?

542
01:13:57,104 --> 01:14:01,400
Play the premiere and all
the performances after it.

543
01:14:01,859 --> 01:14:05,737
- ...not the ones after.
- No, you must, you must!

544
01:14:10,325 --> 01:14:14,246
- Oh, you dear!
- I’m going to Lyuba!

545
01:14:15,247 --> 01:14:17,791
Don’t get run over!

546
01:14:18,208 --> 01:14:23,839
Why did you do it? Who asked you?
Who made you?

547
01:14:25,716 --> 01:14:29,511
Look at yourself.
You’re... an idiot.

548
01:14:29,928 --> 01:14:33,098
You reason like
a three-year-old child.

549
01:14:33,098 --> 01:14:35,100
Why are you sitting there? Stand up!

550
01:14:38,854 --> 01:14:44,568
What am I to do? My God!
Did you think about me? No? No.

551
01:14:49,823 --> 01:14:53,827
You always thought only of yourself.
They’ll lock you up, Yura.

552
01:14:54,453 --> 01:14:57,039
- And rightly so.
- Not rightly so.

553
01:14:57,915 --> 01:15:04,129
Button up. I’ll wait for you, Yura.
Five years, eight years, ten years.

554
01:15:10,385 --> 01:15:15,474
Thank you... ten... ten, so then
I’ll be forty-six.

555
01:15:17,100 --> 01:15:20,312
Yes, that’s, of course...
- My God!

556
01:15:22,481 --> 01:15:25,776
- What have I gotten myself into!
- Into what, huh? Into what?

557
01:15:27,694 --> 01:15:30,656
No, just look,
what you look like...

558
01:15:30,656 --> 01:15:31,740
And what do I look like?

559
01:15:31,990 --> 01:15:35,953
My God, you’ve ruined my whole life,
Yurochka!

560
01:18:35,048 --> 01:18:37,759
Yura!

561
01:19:40,572 --> 01:19:44,701
- Good morning! It’s me!
- Hi!

562
01:19:45,410 --> 01:19:48,997
Have you heard that today
a car was stolen again?

563
01:19:54,336 --> 01:19:57,589
And today, have you looked out the window?

564
01:19:58,465 --> 01:20:03,637
Hello? Hello! Why are you silent?
You’re looking out the window, aren’t you?

565
01:20:04,930 --> 01:20:06,557
So, how is it?

566
01:20:08,475 --> 01:20:11,895
Why did you do it?
Since when have you started stealing

567
01:20:12,187 --> 01:20:16,567
cars from honest people?
Where are your principles?

568
01:20:17,234 --> 01:20:20,904
Oh no! That’s Stelkin’s car—
and he’s a bribe-taker.

569
01:20:21,822 --> 01:20:28,078
What Stelkin? It belongs to a famous scientist!
A Doctor of Sciences!

570
01:20:28,787 --> 01:20:32,416
One moment, I’ll check the card index.

571
01:20:33,292 --> 01:20:37,462
His card index! His card index!
Wretched bureaucrat!

572
01:20:47,473 --> 01:20:50,517
It’s Stelkin’s car—
and he’s a bribe-taker.

573
01:20:58,442 --> 01:21:02,321
It can’t be... did I really make a mistake!

574
01:21:04,615 --> 01:21:09,786
You will drive the Volga back
to its owner immediately. And to you I advise...

575
01:21:11,163 --> 01:21:14,750
Come to me, as they say,
with your things!

576
01:21:15,250 --> 01:21:17,377
And the performance?

577
01:21:20,172 --> 01:21:23,258
There will be no performance!

578
01:21:58,585 --> 01:22:00,462
Come in!

579
01:22:17,646 --> 01:22:20,774
Here is the report on the work done.

580
01:22:32,870 --> 01:22:35,831
The warrant... for my arrest.

581
01:23:31,261 --> 01:23:32,387
Good evening!

582
01:23:32,387 --> 01:23:34,556
- Congratulations on the premiere!
- Same to you.

583
01:23:38,101 --> 01:23:41,021
They brought me such a funny wig!

584
01:23:41,647 --> 01:23:46,860
Why do you need a wig?
Your whole life has been spent in makeup.

585
01:23:48,529 --> 01:23:51,448
And why are you talking about my life
as if it’s already in the past?

586
01:23:51,740 --> 01:23:55,410
Because tomorrow is the trial.
You’re facing five years.

587
01:23:55,702 --> 01:23:59,039
I have mitigating circumstances.
I’m an honest man.

588
01:23:59,873 --> 01:24:05,003
What kind? That you stole cars
from one crook and sold them to another?

589
01:24:06,171 --> 01:24:09,508
Well, my work had some shortcomings.
And who doesn’t?

590
01:24:09,758 --> 01:24:13,178
You, for example, couldn’t catch me
for a very long time.

591
01:24:13,470 --> 01:24:18,100
It’s hard to catch a man
who leads a double life!

592
01:24:18,684 --> 01:24:21,895
I-it always weighed on me terribly,
tormented me.

593
01:24:23,480 --> 01:24:26,233
Uh... tie my bow.

594
01:24:29,778 --> 01:24:33,866
No good deed can be accompanied
by lies and deception.

595
01:24:36,243 --> 01:24:41,123
Imagine that! You took it upon yourself
to pass judgment, to mete out punishment.

596
01:24:44,126 --> 01:24:48,755
To be honest, it’s all foolishness
and a crime.

597
01:24:50,299 --> 01:24:53,051
Defendant, where are you going?

598
01:24:55,387 --> 01:24:56,972
So you also believe

599
01:24:56,972 --> 01:24:58,474
- ...that I’m guilty?
- Yes!

600
01:25:01,560 --> 01:25:05,606
Comrades, the house is full.
Everyone to the stage, please.

601
01:25:05,856 --> 01:25:09,193
Yes, don’t forget to say: “To be or not to be?”
And you’re not ready again?

602
01:25:20,954 --> 01:25:26,710
Here, Hamlet, my handkerchief! Wipe your brow!

603
01:25:28,712 --> 01:25:31,590
The Queen drinks to your success, Hamlet.

604
01:25:33,884 --> 01:25:37,471
But the third time, Laertes, no joking.
Fight with full strength.

605
01:25:37,721 --> 01:25:42,601
- Do you think me a weakling?
- You imagine it? Begin!

606
01:26:07,125 --> 01:26:11,255
Let us forgive each other, noble Hamlet.

607
01:26:11,547 --> 01:26:17,261
Be pure before heaven! I follow you!
Horatio!

608
01:26:18,929 --> 01:26:25,185
- I am dying... mother... farewell!
- Yura, I’m here!

609
01:27:37,466 --> 01:27:38,300
All rise! Court is in session!
We continue the hearing.

610
01:27:47,810 --> 01:27:53,565
Detochkin broke the law, and the law,
as is known, doesn’t like jokes.

611
01:27:54,775 --> 01:27:59,905
In all the judge’s practice,
there has never been such a strange, paradoxical case.

612
01:28:00,948 --> 01:28:05,077
By law, Detochkin faced
imprisonment for up to five years.

613
01:28:06,411 --> 01:28:10,874
Detochkin is not simply a thief. He’s worse!
He’s a bandit!

614
01:28:11,750 --> 01:28:14,294
He must be tried for
armed banditry with breaking and entering!

615
01:28:14,545 --> 01:28:19,675
This type took a swing at what is most sacred to us!
At the Constitution!

616
01:28:20,843 --> 01:28:24,096
It states: “Every person has the right to personal property.

617
01:28:25,305 --> 01:28:28,559
It is protected by law.” Every person has the right to have a car,

618
01:28:28,851 --> 01:28:35,107
a dacha, books... money! Comrades,
money has not yet been abolished.

619
01:28:35,357 --> 01:28:39,903
From each according to ability, to each
according to his labor—in hard cash.

620
01:28:40,195 --> 01:28:45,659
Criminal proceedings have been initiated
against witness Semitsvetov.

621
01:28:46,368 --> 01:28:51,165
Dad! - It’s fine, it’s fine, you’ll find yourself another one—an honest one!

622
01:28:53,333 --> 01:28:56,962
If the future of Dima Semitsvetov
now looked fairly clear,

623
01:28:57,796 --> 01:29:02,551
the fate of Yury Ivanovich Detochkin
still remained uncertain.

624
01:29:03,719 --> 01:29:08,348
At last the court called
the most important witness, Maxim Podberezovikov.

625
01:29:09,475 --> 01:29:11,894
Esteemed comrades judges.

626
01:29:11,894 --> 01:29:15,731
At first I led this case
as an investigator.

627
01:29:17,316 --> 01:29:21,195
But when it turned out that
the defendant is my friend,

628
01:29:22,362 --> 01:29:24,907
I withdrew from the case

629
01:29:24,907 --> 01:29:28,619
and now speak
only as a witness.

630
01:29:30,913 --> 01:29:34,583
I understand, comrades judges, you face
a difficult task:

631
01:29:35,792 --> 01:29:41,924
Detochkin violated the law, but he did so
with noble intentions.

632
01:29:43,425 --> 01:29:48,347
He sold cars, but
gave the money to children.

633
01:29:49,348 --> 01:29:55,604
He is, of course, guilty,
but he... is not guilty.

634
01:29:58,065 --> 01:30:02,694
Have pity on him, comrades judges:
he is a good man.

635
01:30:02,694 --> 01:30:04,321
And an excellent worker!

636
01:30:06,323 --> 01:30:09,701
If you don’t know, then be silent.

637
01:30:15,040 --> 01:30:19,628
Free Yuri Detochkin! Yura!

638
01:30:20,796 --> 01:30:25,300
Quiet! I demand silence, or I will immediately
order the hall cleared!

639
01:30:30,806 --> 01:30:35,102
Defendant, you are given
your final word.

640
01:30:37,604 --> 01:30:42,651
Citizens judges, perhaps I
acted wrongly,

641
01:30:43,068 --> 01:30:48,657
but from a pure heart.
I... couldn’t stand it.

642
01:30:49,158 --> 01:30:54,496
They steal, they steal a lot... I wanted
to help you, citizens judges.

643
01:31:02,838 --> 01:31:07,176
Please let me go!

644
01:31:08,719 --> 01:31:12,389
I won’t do it again...
I swear I won’t!

645
01:31:21,648 --> 01:31:26,612
As is already known, the audience loves detective films.

646
01:31:27,112 --> 01:31:30,491
It’s nice to watch a film,
already knowing how it ends.

647
01:31:31,033 --> 01:31:36,121
This unbelievable story,
which no one knows where took place,

648
01:31:37,331 --> 01:31:42,794
or whether it took place at all,
is coming to an end.

649
01:31:54,306 --> 01:31:58,519
Hello, Lyuba. I’m back.

650
01:32:03,732 --> 01:32:08,946
Russian subtitles at
http://subtitles.ee

651
01:32:14,159 --> 01:32:19,373
29.09.2003

.